	annote = {Hippocampal Neurons Encode Information about Different Types of Memory Episodes Occurring in the Same Location


This study found that rats process information about their environment differently in different situations, even in the same environment. The rats processed right vs left repetition trials in mostly different cells within the hippcampus. I wonder if long term storage of these memories would be closer than in two different situations in different environments. Is the neocortical storage space layed out by location, or other factors?


I would think that environmental location would have something to do with storage location of memories. Different locations would have very different grid, border cell, space cell etc. firing patterns within a memory, while memories in the same location would have very similar firing patterns. I guess a follow up question I would need answered first is if further away imputs (such as olfactory vs visual) would result in hippocampal processing that results in different output locations. This could mean that similar situations are stored close to each other, which through personal experience, I get confused sometimes (ex. which time did I get the burger from my favorite restaurant?) and further apart memories would be less likely to be confused (I never mix up when I walk through my house vs college woods).


Neural Activity in Human Hippocampal Formation Reveals the Spatial Context of Retrieved Memories


So when someone remembers an item, the context such as the spatial location and relative information are also recalled. This could get confusing if the item has to be constantly recalled, reliving a very close episodic memory to the original every time. What seperates these very close memories from enother enough that you can recognize each as its own memory?


I dont actually think we are able to store each instance of a very similar memory. I am not sure if this is why we feel deja vu, or where we have done something but dont remember it. We also blend very similar memories together, such as anual events and not being able to remember each individual thing that happens between years (something like memory blending?). The paper does mention a recent discovery of rat neurons encoding relative times of events, but this opens new questions on what kind of time these encode (daily cycle or up to what year something took place in). 


},
