	year = {1957},
	pages = {11--21},
	annote = {If the hippocampus is the place where all position and episodic information passes through to get to memory, why were the worst patients still able to recall old memories from 3+ years ago?
The hippocampus probably only initiates learning of memories. Once the memory has been remembered and encoded enough times, it is able to be recalled without the hippocampi’s help as its connections in the brain are strong enough. We know that the hippocampus does not store memories both from previous papers (where we learned that positional information at least is stored in the neocortex), as well as the fact that the patients did not lose all of their memories when their hippocampi were disconnected from inputs.
The question above leads me to the next question of, if the hippocampus is not the only pathway for inputs to get to memory, what is/are the other pathway/s and how do the pathways differ? 
I would expect the hippocampal pathway of inputs would be exclusively for creating and maintaining memories, while any other pathway would be for different reasons such as recall of memories. Maybe strong enough memories with strong connections (older + more important) when remembered attempt to avoid using the hippocampus, as creating new pathways and reinforcing them would be power intensive compared to just searching for and retrieving a memory? This type of pathway could survive hippocampal disconection, while still being able to at least recall old memories. 

},
